		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Colorado Springs-10/26/02-End of an Era<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6993'>Patrick "Pappy" Napier</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=6993&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> November 4, 2002</font><p align='justify'><blockquote><font class="bfont"> <br />
<br />
This was it, the last tournament in the Springs before the release of The Two Towers.  I was looking forward to it for about a week, trying to come up with THE deck so I could end the Fellowship block on a good note.  I toyed with the idea of a big Fellowship centered around Aragorn, but the Free People side kept coming out to somewhere around 40 cards, and that only works well with Moria.  I have never been really good at playing Moria decks, and I just never took to them, keeping more with Shadow cultures that were based more on raw Strength.  I decided to stick with what I was used to , and use the Super Archery deck that Brian Montez designed, with a few changes that were more to my taste.  I also decided to stick with Nazgul for my Shadow culture, knowing it had the better chance of beating Danny Hummel’s Hobbit Homosexuality.  Besides, at the last tournament, the deck had three Site 3 victories.   The morning of the event,  Mike Armistead called me up to figure out what time the tournament started, and to let me know he was using a different deck.  I arrived at Hobby Town a few minutes late, but hey, I am the TD, so no worries.  When I arrived, we had nine players including myself, but Mike was on his way from work, so we would have ten and I could play.  Danny Hummel was not there due to work, but we did have Thomas Harris in the house.  David Sampsel also came out of semi-retirement to see if he could back up his smack-talking.   Once Mike arrived, we were all set to play some LOTR.<br />
<br />
GAME ONE <br />
<br />
vs. Joe Schlagheck  Gandalf / Sauron Orcs<br />
<br />
Joe hasn’t been to a tournament in awhile, because he has been active in Boy Scouts.  That always reminds me of Canteen Boy trying to fend off the advances of Alec Baldwin while camping in the woods.  Classic Adam Sandler.  At any rate, I know Joe has a penchant for Sauron, so I am extra comfortable bidding my normal zero.  Joe decides to go first and heads to Site 2 to face Toldea, who wounds Uncommon Legolas twice.  On my turn Joe plays an Orc and UTWE, and the Orc gets shot down.  At Site 3, Cantea comes out to play with a Nazgul Sword, and Toldea shows up as well.  When the dust settles, Gandalf has a Black Breath played on him, and nobody has died.  When I move Joe gets out an Orc Bowmen.  This is going to get nasty if I don’t find some Secret Sentinels soon.  At Site 4 I get out Twilight Nelya and a Blade Tip, which gets put on Aragorn.  At Site 5 Toldea and Attea wielding a Sword bring the attack, with Attea finishing off the Grey Pilgrim.  Toldea loses to Aragorn, who is now carrying a Flaming Brand and his sword.  On my turn I double move to Site 6, which will end up costing me the game.  Legolas gets Hated to death, and I have to take four burdens due to the two copies of Orc Bowmen now out.  Where the Hell are my Secret Sentinels ?  At Site 7 I get out Sam and remove a few burdens, then die to on Orc.  When Joe catches up, the Witch King shows up with a Nazgul Sword, but still cant overwhelm the Prince of Mirkwood, but instead gets a Blade Tip on him.  I finally draw up SS and move to Site 8, canceling his two Bowmen.  It doesn’t matter much, because Arwen gets Hated to death.  Aragorn faces an Orc with a Vile Blade, and actually gets killed.  Stupid card.  Joe has to face down Bill Ferny and Nelya at Site 8, and is not hurt very much.  By this time, if Nazgul have not made a serious dent in his Fellowship, my Shadow side has failed.  It up to my bloodied Fellowship, no consisting of only an exhausted Boromir and Frodo, who are about to go to Site 9.  I cannot use Boromir to trigger my copies of Gondor Bowmen, and the four minions Joe plays are enough to finish me off.  <br />
<br />
FL +1 / +1 <br />
<br />
Great, this day is off to a fabulous start.  But I still have faith that I can win every other game today, because this deck has beaten everyone here.  It turns out that my next opponent had other plans.  <br />
<br />
GAME TWO <br />
<br />
vs.  Keith Davidson  Rangers / Moria<br />
<br />
Keith is a newer player who I have never really considered a threat.  At the last tournament he noticed how my Nazgul were putting the hurt on people by Site 3, so he came prepared.  He won the bid to go first, starting the Pony and playing Aragorn.  He also  plays Gwemegil on Arwen and O Elbereth on Frodo and moves to Site 2.  The only minion I can muster is Twilight Nelya, who Arwen has no trouble dispatching.  He double to Site 3 and again I can only play one minion.  Not good.  On my turn I have every card in my deck in hand to play on Aragorn, so I am set to run as well.  I double to Site 3 also, facing no minions but seeing a couple Goblin Armories played.  At Site 4 Arwen once again holds her own against a Ringwraith.  I face no minions at Site 4.  At the Bridge, I am able to play Attea and Bill Ferny, and since I have no other minions, I have a ton of Twilight left for boosting Attea.  It still is not enough to kill anyone, so Keith doubles to Site 6, where both Boromir and Aragorn end up taking Blade Tips.  When I move to Site 5, I have to sacrifice both Arwen and Legolas to the Balrog, as Aragorn has done directed Archery to whittle down the Swarm.  Nothing much happens for either of us at Site 7.  Before he moves to Site 8, Keith’s Boromir succumbs to the Blade Tip, and Arwen takes a wound.  I am forced to stop at Site 8 after double moving through Site 7 to catch up.  This sets up Keith’s push to Site 9, but before he moves, his Aragorn dies to the Blade Tip.  He tried to play a Saga of Elendil first to keep Aragorn alive for the final move, but I remind him that Blade Tip is at the START of the Fellowship.  This leaves Arwen, Legolas and Frodo, who still bears OEG.  I play Twilight Nelya and Cantea, and unfortunately nothing else.  On the first round, Nelya kills Legolas and Cantea wounds Frodo after the Bounder gets exerted.  On the Fierce, Nelya takes on Arwen while Frodo cancels his Skirmish with OEG, giving Keith the Site 9 victory.  <br />
<br />
FL +1 / +2 <br />
<br />
Well, there goes my rating and my chance at placing in my own tournament.  I have to give Keith credit, even though he teched heavily against Nazgul.  He played smart and assigned Skirmishes the way he was supposed to in order to survive.  Of course, me not drawing any minions early definitely helped him out.  Now I am definitely floundering far from shore in the Sea of Jizz.<br />
<br />
GAME THREE <br />
<br />
vs.  David Sampsel  Boromir & Pippin / Nazgul<br />
<br />
David has come out of hiding, as I said earlier.  He is a long time card player and used to come to nearly all of my Star Wars events.  David has talked a lot about how is deck is a beast, but so far has not won a game yet today.  I guess that’s why he has to play me.  Lets see if he can not just sing it but bring it.  He bids one and makes me go first, which means he is playing Nazgul.  I redraw my hand, get Aragorn and his Ranger’s Sword and move to his Site 2, Weatherhills.  Excellent, he IS playing Nazgul.  I handle whatever he throws my way, then get set to pummel his Fellowship.  He starts by playing Gandalf and some toys, then moves.  He has to face Attea, Toldea and to Blade Tips right away.  Boromir gets a Tip and takes two wounds, while Pippen dies, and Gandalf gets the second Tip in the Fierce Skirmish.  David stops.  I move to the Ford and shoot down whatever Rag he threw at me.  When Dave’s turn started, Boromir took a dirt nap, and Gandalf took another wound.  He now has Frodo and Gandalf going to the Ford.  I play Cantea for free and Gates in a Witch King.  Frodo looks across the River Bruinen at the Ringwraiths, his bowels loosen and a dark wet spot appears at the crotch of his Little Hobbit Breeches ( haha haven’t used that in awhile ) <br />
<br />
FW +3 / +5<br />
<br />
Yay for me, I am slowly swimming my way out of The Salty Sea of Jizz.  If I can win my next two games, I will at least continue to play this game.  If not, well . . .<br />
<br />
GAME FOUR <br />
<br />
vs. Tai Tran  Dwarves / Sauron<br />
<br />
tai loves his Sauron Orcs.  He has played Sauron in every tournament, I think.  He loves to play Enheartened Foe and Enduring Evil and jank like that.  When he shows his starting Fellowship of Gimli and Fror, I know the game is mine.  He bids to go first, and starts Hobbiton Woods.  He moves to Site 2 and gives me 5 Twilight, so I pass.  He stops.  On my turn I play Aragorn and Boromir and Blade of Gondor.  A Gondor Bowmen also hits the table.  Tai plays an Orc Inquisitor and discards a Witch King at random from my hand.  Oh swell.  Boromir handles the Orc no problem.  At Site 3 I play a Cantea, and do a little damage, but Gimli will heal next turn.  My Archery and the Blade of Gondor take care of any Orc that Tai plays at Site 3.  When Tai moves to the Moria Sairway, he faces Toldea with a Sword, and Gimli gets a Blade Tip and Black Breat for his trouble.  I mow through his Orcs at Site 4, including using Boromir to stab a Morgul Hunter.  At the hated Bridge, Gimli falls to a Witch King and Fror gets a Blade Tip / Black Breath combo on him.  When I move to the Bridge, Aragorn gets Hated to death.  Yeah, that makes sense.  At Site 6, Tai is faced with Attea, who kills Fror.  Attea shows up again at Site 7 and puts a hurting on Farin.  On my turn I double through to Site 8 after Tai draws up no minions.  This puts the pressure on Tai, but it all ends at Site 8 for him when his Farin and Frodo encounter Cantea and Toldea ( insert Little Hobbit Breeches joke here ) <br />
<br />
FW +3 / +8 <br />
<br />
Oh boy, oh boy, one more game to go and I can go have a beer with Mike.  <br />
<br />
GAME FIVE <br />
<br />
vs.  Matt Deloux  Rangers / Uruk-Hai<br />
<br />
Matt is a decent player who just lacks the right cards to really make his deck work for him.  As much as we all want this game to work with Commons and Uncommons, most of the time a huge Pile O’ Rares will come out ahead.  ( unless the strategy is so tight with a Common deck, which is rarely seen )  Matt wins the bid and goes first, playing a bow on Arwen and pulling Aragorn with the Pony.  When Matt moves to Weatherhills, the Witch King is waiting to bring the pain, along with Cantea.  The Lord of Angmar overwhelms Legolas and Arwen, while Aragorn takes on Cantea.  I guess Matt just really didn’t want to lose the Heir to Gondor this early in the game.   On his next turn, Toldea, Cantea and Bill Ferny show up at the Ford after Matt gave enough Twilight by playing Erestor and healing Elrond.  Matt brings up Erestor and Elrond to help out.  Elrond takes a wound in round one, while Erestor dies, then Aragorn is killed by Toldea in the Fierce Skirmish, Elrond taking another wound.  This leaves Frodo all alone at the Sanctuary.  <br />
When Matt move his lone Frodo to Site 4, there is not enough Twilight for me to play anyone.  Frodo’s end came when Matt moved to the Bridge and both Attea and Cantea sealed his fate.<br />
During this whole time, my Fellowship never had to Skirmish, as Archery mowed down any Uruk-Hai that made it on to the table.  <br />
<br />
FW + 3 / +11<br />
<br />
After the game Matt and I analyze his deck and come up with some ideas.  The only problem is he needs a few more Rares to pull it off.  We worked with what he had, and he took to heart some of the suggested cards he should try to acquire.  Hopefully he will make a strong showing next time around. <br />
<br />
So I end the day at 3 and 2, and very disappointed in my performance at the last event before TTT .  Thomas Harris takes First and Mike comes in Second.  Matt Deloux gets the Participation award.  I make a few trades for some foils, bringing me down to needing about 78 or so to finish my set of Fellowship foils.  After the event Mike and I head to Bennigan’s for a couple pints of the good stuff, Guinness.  We talk about some of the changes the game will go through, and whether or not my next event should be Two Towers only format  ( any players in my area who read this give your input in your review ).  We also joke about how we hope Joe Alread doesn’t make some mechanics in this set that are broken and need errata out of the box, and then we piss an moan about how Podracing ruined Star Wars.  Until next time, folks, when TTT has been out.  <br />
<br />
PROPS <br />
<br />
To everyone who came, making the event fun and sanctioned.<br />
<br />
To everyone who traded.<br />
<br />
To Keith Davidson, for playing smart, even though you totally tweaked your deck for Nazgul.  Next time I’m pulling your card.  <br />
<br />
SLOPS<br />
<br />
To Nazgul, for failing in late game, and to Secret Sentinels, for never showing up against wounding Sauron Orcs.<br />
<br />
To Joe Alread, for inventing Podracing.  <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
